62
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:46,860
But the need to fill the void in its place, that remains.

63
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:49,379
And while another character in Dostoevsky's "Demons" says,

64
00:02:46,860 --> 00:02:52,500
"If there is no God, then what kind of captain am I?"

65
00:02:49,379 --> 00:02:55,019
Kirillov says, "If there is no God, then I can take His place."

66
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:58,860
Kirillov says, "If there is no God, then I can take His place."

67
00:02:55,019 --> 00:02:59,940
Remember, Grebenshikov sang:

68
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:03,120
"Do you feel the draft because this place is vacant?"

69
00:02:59,940 --> 00:03:06,500
Kirillov feels that very draft, and

70
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:10,620
formulates a terrifying, insane thought

71
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:13,200
that he later falls in love with.

72
00:03:10,620 --> 00:03:15,659
"If a person," he says,

73
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:19,019
"decides to express their will,

74
00:03:15,659 --> 00:03:21,900
not out of anger, fear, or malice,

75
00:03:19,019 --> 00:03:23,760
but simply because they have the right,

76
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:27,540
and leaves life, then,"

77
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:30,060
Kirillov argues, "this step will transform

78
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:32,459
all humanity and he himself

79
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:34,379
will become a man-god."

80
00:03:32,459 --> 00:03:36,900

79
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:34,379
Step by step, all of humanity

80
00:03:32,459 --> 00:03:36,900
and even God Himself will become human.

81
00:03:34,379 --> 00:03:40,500
"But there have already been millions of suicides,"

82
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:43,400
they tell him, "all in vain, all with fear and not for that purpose,"

83
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:47,040
Kirillov replies.

84
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:49,680
And his insane approach remarkably resembles

85
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:52,799
an episode from "Don Quixote."

86
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:54,900
Remember when Sancho Panza says daringly

87
00:03:52,799 --> 00:03:57,420
and far ahead that he plans to emulate

88
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:58,879
the glorious knights of the past and go mad.

89
00:03:57,420 --> 00:04:02,220
The pragmatic Sancho then asks,

90
00:03:58,879 --> 00:04:04,019
"But do you have a reason to go mad, sir?

91
00:04:02,220 --> 00:04:07,980
What could the reason be?"

92
00:04:04,019 --> 00:04:10,980
— "That's the whole point,"

93
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:12,900
Don Quixote answers.

94
00:04:10,980 --> 00:04:15,599
"That's the peculiarity of my planned undertaking.

95
00:04:12,900 --> 00:04:18,000
If a knight-errant goes mad

96
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:20,519
for some reason, don't expect any reward or gratitude."

97
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,160
.

98
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:26,340
.

96
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:20,519
If a knight has gone mad for any reason,

97
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,160
don’t ask for rewards or

98
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:26,340
gratitude. The whole point is

99
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:29,460
to go mad without any reason.

100
00:04:26,340 --> 00:04:31,979
And, as we’ll soon see, these echoes

101
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:33,300
in the words of Kirillov and Quixote are

102
00:04:31,979 --> 00:04:36,180
far from coincidental.

